---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'document';
const description =
  'Delta-refresh stale CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md / .cursor/rules without nuking history. Marks the old rule deprecated with a date and reason. Never silently rewrites.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands" eyebrow="Command">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    <a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a> is for repos with
    nothing. <code>document</code> is for repos with something, either stale
    context files or a mature codebase that has never had context files
    before. The difference matters: <code>document</code> does delta updates
    that preserve history.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    Most teams write a <code>CLAUDE.md</code> once. Then the stack changes.
    Yarn becomes pnpm. Jest becomes Vitest. The convention "components live in
    <code>src/components/</code>" silently becomes "components live in
    <code>app/(routes)/</code>" because Next.js shipped a new pattern. The
    context file does not change. The agent confidently follows the old rules
    and produces non-working scripts. The team blames AI; the real failure is
    ContextOps.
  </p>
  <p>
    <code>document</code> closes that gap. But the natural instinct, "just
    rewrite the file from scratch", is wrong. Rewrites lose the
    <em>why</em>, which is the most valuable thing in the file. The old rule
    existed for a reason. That reason is often still relevant context for the
    next decision.
  </p>
  <p>
    So <code>document</code> does delta merges. The new rule is added with a
    date. The old rule is moved to a <code>## Deprecated</code> block with the
    date deprecated and the reason. A future agent reading the file knows both
    the current rule and the history. Intent debt, paid.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      The model is from the
      <a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>ContextOps lifecycle</a>
      (Update stage, delta over rewrites) and the
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>good practices</a> doc
      ("Delta updates over rewrites").
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Stack changed. New test framework, new package manager, new build tool.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>CLAUDE.md</code> exists but the agent keeps producing code that
      does not match the current code.
    </li>
    <li>
      Mature repo adopting Groundwork for the first time. The repo has years
      of accumulated convention in the code but nothing written down.
    </li>
    <li>
      After running <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> and
      seeing "stale context" findings.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <p>The same set of files as <code>init</code>, with these differences:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Existing files are not overwritten. They are extended.</li>
    <li>Stale sections are marked deprecated with a date and reason.</li>
    <li>The chat summary names <em>what changed</em>: added, deprecated, kept.</li>
    <li>The agent reads the last 50 commits to spot recent convention shifts.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Detect what exists.</strong> Globs every known context-file
      location. Reads each. Notes last-modified date and approximate accuracy.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Read the repo deeply.</strong> Last 50 commits. Random sample of
      recent files in each major directory. Checks whether the conventions in
      the existing files match the actual code.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ask three focused questions.</strong> Which detected rules are
      still correct? Which new patterns should be written in? Anything you
      want explicitly marked deprecated?
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Delta-merge.</strong> Sections still correct: keep verbatim.
      Sections that drifted: append the corrected content, dated, with the old
      one moved to a deprecated block. New sections: append at the bottom of
      the relevant area.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reconcile across harnesses.</strong> If <code>CLAUDE.md</code>
      and <code>AGENTS.md</code> disagree, the disagreement is surfaced. The
      command does not silently pick a winner.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Verify.</strong> Same verification commands, same fail-loudly
      behaviour as <code>init</code>.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="What deprecation looks like" tone="mute">
    <p>An emitted section, after a stack change:</p>
    <pre><code>## Test framework

Vitest (since 2026-04). Faster, native ESM, drop-in for Jest.
Run: pnpm test.

## Deprecated

### Test framework: Jest (until 2026-04)
Migrated away due to ESM friction with our Vite setup.</code></pre>
    <p>
      The next agent reading the file knows the current rule and why the old
      one existed. The team's collective theory survives the change.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Rewriting from scratch.</strong> If you find yourself blanking
      the file, you are running the wrong command. Switch to <code>init</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Trusting the old file.</strong> The old file is the source of
      historical truth. The code is the source of current truth. When they
      disagree, the code wins; the old file gets deprecated.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Skipping the git history scan.</strong> Recent commits are the
      cheapest possible signal for "what changed lately".
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>ContextOps lifecycle</a>.
      Update stage, delta over rewrites.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>Good practices</a>. Delta
      updates, why rewrites lose intent.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>Cognitive debt</a>. Intent
      debt is the most subtle form, and the one rewrites accelerate.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#contextops')}>2026 Blueprint: delta updates</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="document" />
</Doc>
